name: TIME_1
description: The word "alligator" comes from the Spanish word "el lagarto," which means "the lizard."

name: TIME_2
description: Agouti looks like a close relative of guinea pig. It has slender body covered with two-colored, glossy fur.

name: TIME_3
description: Ants are the longest living of all insects, living for up to 30 years.

name: TIME_4
description: Puffins are fab flyers, flapping their wings up to 400 times a minute and speeding through the air at up to 88km an hour. Wow!

name: TIME_5
description: Barn Owls screech – they never hoot (that’s Tawny Owls).

name: TIME_6
description: Badgers are part of the family Mustelidae this is the same family as otters, ferret, polecats, weasels and wolverines.

name: TIME_7
description: Bees are the only insect in the world that make food that people can eat

name: TIME_8
description: Beetles are incredibly versatile and are found nearly everywhere on Earth except for the very cold polar regions.

name: TIME_9
description: Bisons have a thick, brown coat that provides insulation from the cold and moist weather. It prevents melting of the snow and soaking of the skin.

name: TIME_10
description: What really makes Black Mambas a deadly serpent is its speed. It is the fastest known land snake known to mankind. They slither at a speed of 12.5 miles an hour.

name: TIME_11
description: The Black Widow spider is the most poisonous spider in North America, but only the adult female.

name: TIME_12
description: Bunnies eat grass, clovers, wild flowers and farm crops.  Bunnies also eat their own poop.

name: TIME_13
description: Butterflies can see red, green, and yellow.

name: TIME_14
description: The word 'camel' comes from an Arabic word: ǧml. This word is literally translated to mean Beauty. Don't ever say that camels are ugly!

name: TIME_15
description: The scientific name for capybara comes from Hydro chaeris, which means "water hog" in Greek.

name: TIME_16
description: Caracal is not afraid to attack animal that is three times bigger of its size.

name: TIME_17
description: Caribou releases special scent when faced with danger. Scent is produced in the gland located in the base of ankles and it informs other caribous about near danger.

name: TIME_18
description: A group of cats is called a “clowder.”

name: TIME_19
description: Centipedes do NOT have one hundred legs.

name: TIME_20
description: Chameleon eyes have a 360-degree arc of vision and can see two directions at once.

name: TIME_21
description: Chickens aren’t completely flightless—they can get airborne enough to make it over a fence or into a tree.

name: TIME_22
description: Chinchilla is nocturnal animal, active from the dusk to the dawn. Night decreases visibility and provides protection against predators.

name: TIME_23
description: The cheetah is the world’s fastest land animal. They can run 70 mph (or 110 kph), which is as fast as cars drive on the highway.

name: TIME_24
description: The clownfish is also known as the anemonefish.

name: TIME_25
description: Cows can’t vomit.

name: TIME_26
description: Even though coyotes look like dogs, they’re wild. If you see one, yell and back away slowly.

name: TIME_27
description: A crab may lose a claw or leg in a fight. In time, the claw or leg grows back.

name: TIME_28
description: The expression "cry crocodile tears" is based on a true fact - crocodiles produce tears when they eat.

name: TIME_29
description: Deers can jump high and swim well.

name: TIME_30
description: Dolphins compared to other animals, dolphins are believed to be very intelligent.

name: TIME_31
description: A donkey will never get involved in an activity if it considers it to be unsafe

name: TIME_32
description: Dragonflies are expert fliers. They can fly straight up and down, hover like a helicopter and even mate mid-air. If they can’t fly, they’ll starve because they only eat prey they catch while flying.

name: TIME_33
description: A common urban legend is that a ducks quack does not echo. This has however, been proven to be false.

name: TIME_34
description: Ducklings first recognize their mother's calling sounds, in their first days after hatching.

name: TIME_35
description: Bald eagles aren’t actually bald.

name: TIME_36
description: Lacking lungs or other specialized respiratory organs, earthworms breathe through their skin.

name: TIME_37
description: Elephants are the largest land animals in the world therefore they are unable to jump.

name: TIME_38
description: The unique sound made by an elk is known as a bark or a bugle.

name: TIME_39
description: Emu is a fast running animal. It can reach 30 miles per hour.

name: TIME_40
description: Doves are often referred to as “A Pigeon with a good PR agent”.

name: TIME_41
description: Erect-crested penguin has spikes on the tongue and back of the mouth which facilitate holding and swallowing of prey in one piece.

name: TIME_42
description: The color pink comes from beta-carotene in the crustaceans and plankton that flamingos eat.

name: TIME_43
description: Flatworms can glide over surfaces, or the underside of a surface film of water, using small body hairs for movement.

name: TIME_44
description: Foxes are generally solitary animals; unlike wolves, they hunt on their own rather than in packs.

name: TIME_45
description: When dogs poop, they prefer to do it in alignment with the Earth's magnetic field. Freya doesn't care about that though.

name: TIME_46
description: A frog completely sheds its skin about once a week. After it pulls off the old, dead skin, the frog usually eats it.

name: TIME_47
description: Giraffes require over 75 pounds of food a day—and with a diet of leaves, this means they spend most of their time eating.

name: TIME_48
description: Goats were one of the first animals to be tamed by humans and were being herded 9,000 years ago.

name: TIME_49
description: Gorillas have unique noseprints, much like human fingerprints, which can be used to identify individuals.

name: TIME_50
description: Grasshoppers can jump about 25cm high and around 1 meter long. If humans could jump as far as grasshoppers do, relative to size, then we could leap more than the length of a football field.

name: TIME_51
description: The grey crowned cranes enjoy dancing.

name: TIME_52
description: Guinea pigs are very social animals and they are much happier when kept in pairs or groups.

name: TIME_53
description: Hamsters can store food in their cheeks, then eat it later!

name: TIME_54
description: A hedgehog has between 5000 and 7000 quills.

name: TIME_55
description: Hermit crabs often exchange and occasionally fight with other hermit crabs to conquer better shells.

name: TIME_56
description: Hippos can’t swim or float! They walk or stand on surfaces below the water like sandbanks. Even so, they spend most of the day in water to protect their sensitive skin from the sun.

name: TIME_57
description: Hornets attack humans in self-defense. Painful sting may end up fatally when person is allergic to the venom. Each hornet can sting couple of times.

name: TIME_58
description: Horses can sleep both lying down and standing up.

name: TIME_59
description: The name ‘Impala’ come from the Zulu language meaning ‘gazelle’.

name: TIME_60
description: The jaguar has a very powerful jaw, its bite exerts more force than that of a lion.

name: TIME_61
description: Some species of jellyfish are immortal.

name: TIME_62
description: Jackals respond only to the sounds produced by the members of their family. They ignore all other calls.

name: TIME_63
description: An Arctic Fox can survive in extremely low temperatures, sometimes reach as low as -58 degrees!

name: TIME_64
description: Vampire bats have small and extremely sharp teeth which are capable of piercing an animal’s skin (humans included) without them even noticing.

name: TIME_65
description: Beavers are slow on land but using their webbed feet, they are very good swimmers. A beaver can stay under water for up to 15 minutes.

name: TIME_66
description: Adult cow males that are not castrated are generally called bulls.

name: TIME_67
description: When chimpanzees are bored, they organize various games to entertain themselves.

name: TIME_68
description: Coelacanths were thought to be extinct until a live one was caught in 1938

name: TIME_69
description: Crows are emotional animals. They react to hunger and invasion by vigorously vocalizing their feelings. They display happiness, anger and sadness.

name: TIME_70
description: Ermine moves in a zigzag manner, bouncing 20 inches from the ground after each leap. It can travel more than 9 miles per night to find food.

name: TIME_71
description: Geese fly in a “V” formation. If one goose is injured, other geese will stay with it until it dies or can rejoin the flock.

name: TIME_72
description: Hawks have excellent eyesight. They can see 8 times better than humans. Eyesight is primarily used for hunting. Hawk can locate its prey from a distance of 100 feet.

name: TIME_73
description: Hummingbirds are the only birds that can fly backwards.

name: TIME_74
description: Spotted hyenas are also known as laughing hyenas. Why? Because these highly intelligent creatures communicate with yells, whoops and cackles – some of which can be heard almost 5km away!

name: TIME_75
description: The King Cobra is the longest venomous snake in the world.

name: TIME_76
description: Kangaroos have very powerful legs and can be dangerous at times.

name: TIME_77
description: Kingfishers have a hard beak like a dagger for spearing fish.

name: TIME_78
description: Kittens can fit their bodies anywhere they can fit their heads

name: TIME_79
description: Koalas eat eucalypt leaves and almost nothing else.

name: TIME_80
description: Komodo dragons often fight with other dragons. They bite each other during the fight, but unlike other animals, they are immune to bacteria from their saliva.

name: TIME_81
description: Ladybugs aren't really bugs. They're beetles!

name: TIME_82
description: The Lemur is a native animal of Madagascar.

name: TIME_83
description: Leopards are great climbers and great swimmers.

name: TIME_84
description: A lion’s roar can be heard from as far as 5 miles away.

name: TIME_85
description: Lizards are reptiles.

name: TIME_86
description: Llamas are known as animals that spit when provoked or threatened. They can spit at humans also, but they usually spit at each other to solve misunderstandings in the group.

name: TIME_87
description: Lynx is not a fast runner. Since it does not chase the prey, it hunts from an ambush and uses the element of surprise.

name: TIME_88
description: Manatees have no natural predators in the wild but humans have played a large part in making all three species at risk of extinction.

name: TIME_89
description: A clan of meerkats will always have one "sentry" on guard to watch out for predators while the others forage for food.

name: TIME_90
description: Groups of monkeys are known as a ‘tribe’, ‘troop’ or ‘mission’.

name: TIME_91
description: Moose have 32 teeth in total. Their front teeth are missing.

name: TIME_92
description: Moths use moon, stars and geomagnetic field to navigate during the flight.

name: TIME_93
description: Mountain goats are not in the same genus as goats. In the bovidae family, mountain goats are associated with antelopes, gazelles and cattle.

name: TIME_94
description: Mice use their whiskers to sense changes in temperature and to help feel the surface they are walking along.

name: TIME_95
description: Musk oxen have two glands under their eyes that produce musk, which is a strong odor.

name: TIME_96
description: Narwhal's tusk can grow to be 10 feet long

name: TIME_97
description: Unlike other cat species, ocelots are not afraid of the water. They are excellent swimmers.

name: TIME_98
description: Octopus have 3 hearts and their blood is blue in color.

name: TIME_99
description: Okapi slightly resembles to zebra because of the stripes, but it shares much more similarities with giraffe. It has long skull, large black eyes and very long, purplish tongue, just like giraffe.

name: TIME_100
description: Orangutans are gentle and sit for hours gazing.

name: TIME_101
description: Orcas ("The Killer Whale") is not a whale. It's a dolphin! And eats sharks!

name: TIME_102
description: The otter is a very playful animal and are believe to take part in some activities just for the enjoyment. Some make waterslides to slide down into the water!

name: TIME_103
description: Owls can rotate their necks 270 degrees. A blood-pooling system collects blood to power their brains and eyes when neck movement cuts off circulation.

name: TIME_104
description: Pandas are BIG eaters – every day they fill their tummies for up to 12 hours, shifting up to 12 kilograms of bamboo!

name: TIME_105
description: Parrots are believed to be one of the most intelligent bird species.

name: TIME_106
description: "Peacock" is commonly used as the name for a peafowl of the pheasant family. But in fact "peacock" is the name for the colorfully plumaged male peafowl only.

name: TIME_107
description: Penguins are flightless birds.

name: TIME_108
description: Pigeons were used as mail carriers during the First and Second World War. They saved numerous lives by delivering information on the enemy's fire.

name: TIME_109

name: TIME_110
description: Platypus don't have a stomach.

name: TIME_111
description: Polar bears clean themselves by rolling in the snow.

name: TIME_112
description: Mantids have two eyes,but only one ear.

name: TIME_113
description: Pumas can run up to 80 kph (50 mph) and jump as high as 4.6 meters (15 feet).

name: TIME_114
description: A rabbit’s teeth never stop growing. Fortunately, they’re naturally kept short by the normal wear and tear of chewing. Lots and lots of chewing, that is — about 120 times a minute.

name: TIME_115
description: A raccoon’s hands are so nimble they can unlace a shoe, unlatch a cage and deftly retrieve coins as thin as dimes from your shirt pocket.

name: TIME_116
description: Red Panda's were the inspiration behind the name of an Internet Browser (Mozilla Firefox).

name: TIME_117
description: The name rhinoceros means ‘nose horn’ and is often shortened to rhino.

name: TIME_118
description: Sea lions can dive up to 1,000 feet!

name: TIME_119
description: Sea snakes are very poisonous. Watch out!

name: TIME_120
description: Skunks can spray its oily and smelly substance up to 10 feet distance.

name: TIME_123
description: A swan will mate for life.

name: TIME_126
description: A tortoise is a turtle, but a turtle isn't a tortoise.

name: TIME_127
description: The toucan has small wings therefore they are not very good at flying and cannot stay airborne for long.

name: TIME_128
description: Turtles belong to one of the oldest reptile groups in the world – beating snakes, crocodiles and alligators!

name: TIME_135
description: Zebras stand up while sleeping.

name: TIME_137

name: TIME_145
description: Stingrays aren't normally aggressive.

name: TIME_147
description: Freya really enjoys her naps.

name: TIME_148
description: Freya is actually concerned about stuff in general.

name: TIME_149
description: Freya also enjoys stealing rolls of toilet paper. Who doesn't?

name: TIME_150
description: The honey badger is a badass, he doesn't care, he'll smash everything that opposes him.
